{"id":19161,"date":"2023-11-17T03:09:59","date_gmt":"2023-11-17T11:09:59","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/?p=19161"},"modified":"2023-11-17T03:17:53","modified_gmt":"2023-11-17T11:17:53","slug":"the-salmon-run-in-british-columbia","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/2023\/11\/17\/the-salmon-run-in-british-columbia\/","title":{"rendered":"THE SALMON RUN in BRITISH COLUMBIA"},"content":{"rendered":"<header class=\"entry-header header-singular wrapper\">\n<h1 class=\"entry-title article-heading\">Where to See the Salmon Run in British Columbia: Complete Guide<\/h1>\n<\/header>\n<div class=\"entry-content mvt-content\" data-content-ads-inserted=\"true\">\n<p>Excerpted from https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/Published September 2023<\/p>\n<p>As the Pacific salmon swim from the ocean to the spawning grounds of their birth, British Columbia becomes the host of one of the most breathtaking wildlife migrations in the world.<br \/>\nDuring this time, BC\u2019s rivers and creeks teem with salmon fighting their way upstream, through rapids and cascades, sometimes leaping out of the water to ascend obstacles.<br \/>\nThe annual salmon run is an impressive sight and one definitely not to miss when travelling the province in autumn.<\/p>\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\" data-slot-rendered-content=\"true\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-medium\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" id=\"mv-trellis-img-1\" class=\"wp-image-32729 eager-load\" src=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/salmon-puntledge-hatchery-courtenay-563x750.jpg.webp\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 760px) calc(100vw - 20px), 720px\" srcset=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/salmon-puntledge-hatchery-courtenay-563x750.jpg.webp 563w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/salmon-puntledge-hatchery-courtenay-150x200.jpg.webp 150w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/salmon-puntledge-hatchery-courtenay-768x1024.jpg.webp 768w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/salmon-puntledge-hatchery-courtenay-546x728.jpg.webp 546w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/salmon-puntledge-hatchery-courtenay-720x960.jpg.webp 720w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/salmon-puntledge-hatchery-courtenay-810x1080.jpg.webp 810w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/salmon-puntledge-hatchery-courtenay-900x1200.jpg.webp 900w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/salmon-puntledge-hatchery-courtenay-640x853.jpg.webp 640w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/salmon-puntledge-hatchery-courtenay.jpg.webp 1000w\" alt=\"Close up of salmon in observation tank at Puntledge River Hatchery, one of the best places to see the salmon run in BC\" width=\"563\" height=\"750\" data-pin-media=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/salmon-puntledge-hatchery-courtenay.jpg\" data-src=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/salmon-puntledge-hatchery-courtenay-563x750.jpg.webp\" data-srcset=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/salmon-puntledge-hatchery-courtenay-563x750.jpg.webp 563w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/salmon-puntledge-hatchery-courtenay-150x200.jpg.webp 150w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/salmon-puntledge-hatchery-courtenay-768x1024.jpg.webp 768w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/salmon-puntledge-hatchery-courtenay-546x728.jpg.webp 546w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/salmon-puntledge-hatchery-courtenay-720x960.jpg.webp 720w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/salmon-puntledge-hatchery-courtenay-810x1080.jpg.webp 810w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/salmon-puntledge-hatchery-courtenay-900x1200.jpg.webp 900w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/salmon-puntledge-hatchery-courtenay-640x853.jpg.webp 640w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/salmon-puntledge-hatchery-courtenay.jpg.webp 1000w\" data-svg=\"1\" data-trellis-processed=\"1\" \/><figcaption>Puntledge Hatchery<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<\/div>\n<p>In this post, I\u2019ll share some of the best places to watch the salmon run in British Columbia.<br \/>\nDespite calling BC home for 10+ years, I am still awe-struck by the strength and determination of the salmon.<br \/>\nWe are fortunate to be able to see (kokanee) salmon running in our home town of Penticton, just a few streets away from our house. I try not to take it for granted, however, and visit other locations when we can. Read on to discover the best spots!<\/p>\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-medium\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" id=\"mv-trellis-img-2\" class=\"wp-image-32938 lazyload\" src=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/salmon-puntledge-river-autumn-bc-1000x750.jpg.webp\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 760px) calc(100vw - 20px), 720px\" srcset=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/salmon-puntledge-river-autumn-bc-1000x750.jpg.webp 1000w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/salmon-puntledge-river-autumn-bc-267x200.jpg.webp 267w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/salmon-puntledge-river-autumn-bc-768x576.jpg.webp 768w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/salmon-puntledge-river-autumn-bc-728x546.jpg.webp 728w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/salmon-puntledge-river-autumn-bc-960x720.jpg.webp 960w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/salmon-puntledge-river-autumn-bc-1080x810.jpg.webp 1080w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/salmon-puntledge-river-autumn-bc-1200x900.jpg.webp 1200w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/salmon-puntledge-river-autumn-bc-853x640.jpg.webp 853w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/salmon-puntledge-river-autumn-bc-150x113.jpg.webp 150w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/salmon-puntledge-river-autumn-bc.jpg.webp 1240w\" alt=\"Looking down from bridge into Puntledge RIver, with many fins close to surface (salmon running)\" width=\"1000\" height=\"750\" data-pin-media=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/salmon-puntledge-river-autumn-bc.jpg\" data-trellis-processed=\"1\" \/><figcaption>Watching the salmon run in Morrison Creek, next to Puntledge River on Vancouver Island<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<\/div>\n<div id=\"grow-me-inline-subscribe-cta-root-0\" data-testid=\"inline-subscribe-cta-0\">\n<div class=\"notranslate\" data-nosnippet=\"true\">\n<div class=\"ShadowDomContainer___StyledDiv-paiu0k-0\">\n<div class=\"SpotlightSubscribeForm___StyledDiv2-sc-156rk68-1 efqzKA test\">\n<div class=\"SpotlightSubscribeForm___StyledDiv3-sc-156rk68-2 QenpA\">\n<div class=\"SubscribeCtaWidget___StyledDiv4-xaybyu-7 gIBsiR\" data-testid=\"inline-subscribe\">\n<div class=\"SubscribeCtaWidget___StyledDiv-xaybyu-0 hhNdCo\"><\/div>\n<div class=\"SubscribeCtaWidget___StyledDiv2-xaybyu-2 dUWrkg\">\n<div>\n<div class=\"SubscribeCtaWidget___StyledDiv3-xaybyu-3 fULgJv\"><\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<h2>BC\u2019s salmon run: the basics<\/h2>\n<p data-slot-rendered-content=\"true\"><span style=\"font-size: 12px;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><strong>What does it mean to see the salmon run?<\/strong><\/span><br \/>\n<\/span>There are five Pacific salmon species indigenous to British Columbia \u2013 chinook, chum,\u00a0sockeye, coho, and pink. BC is also home to kokanee salmon, a form of \u2018landlocked\u2019 sockeye that do not migrate to the sea.<br \/>\nPacific salmon start their lives in freshwater rivers, later migrating to the ocean where they grow and mature for several years. Eventually, they return to the very same river they originated from to reproduce, completing their life cycle before passing away.<br \/>\nTravelling back to their origin point is not easy for salmon, however. These tenacious fish spend weeks fighting against the current, leaping cascades, dodging rocks and avoiding predators.<br \/>\nMany do not make it to their final destination (only 1-2% are successful).<br \/>\nOf course, it\u2019s a humbling realisation to realise that those that do make it, die anyway. This dangerous journey is the culmination of the salmon\u2019s life. For this reason, the salmon run is a symbol of the circle of life.<\/p>\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\" data-slot-rendered-content=\"true\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-medium\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" id=\"mv-trellis-img-3\" class=\"wp-image-4544 lazyload\" src=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/03\/salmon-spawning-in-valdez-1000x750.jpg.webp\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 760px) calc(100vw - 20px), 720px\" srcset=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/03\/salmon-spawning-in-valdez.jpg.webp 1000w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/03\/salmon-spawning-in-valdez-267x200.jpg.webp 267w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/03\/salmon-spawning-in-valdez-768x576.jpg.webp 768w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/03\/salmon-spawning-in-valdez-150x113.jpg.webp 150w\" alt=\"Dozens of salmon fins at surface of water during the salmon run \" width=\"1000\" height=\"750\" data-pin-media=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/03\/salmon-spawning-in-valdez.jpg\" data-trellis-processed=\"1\" \/><figcaption>The salmon run involes many thousands of fish<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<\/div>\n<h3><strong>When is the salmon run in BC?<\/strong><\/h3>\n<p>The salmon run is an annual occurrence, with the main spawning season for Pacific salmon taking place in autumn.<br \/>\nThe actual timing varies between species and locations. It also changes from year to year, sometimes occurring slightly earlier and sometimes slightly later. As a general rule, late September to late October is the peak time for the salmon run in BC.<\/p>\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\" data-slot-rendered-content=\"true\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-medium\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" id=\"mv-trellis-img-4\" class=\"wp-image-33136 lazyload\" src=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/baileys-chute-wells-gray-salmon-997x750.jpg.webp\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 760px) calc(100vw - 20px), 720px\" srcset=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/baileys-chute-wells-gray-salmon-997x750.jpg.webp 997w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/baileys-chute-wells-gray-salmon-266x200.jpg.webp 266w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/baileys-chute-wells-gray-salmon-768x578.jpg.webp 768w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/baileys-chute-wells-gray-salmon-960x722.jpg.webp 960w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/baileys-chute-wells-gray-salmon-1080x813.jpg.webp 1080w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/baileys-chute-wells-gray-salmon-150x113.jpg.webp 150w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/baileys-chute-wells-gray-salmon.jpg.webp 1200w\" alt=\"Salmon jumping up rapids at Baileys Chute, a raging torrent of water\" width=\"997\" height=\"750\" data-pin-media=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/baileys-chute-wells-gray-salmon.jpg\" data-trellis-processed=\"1\" \/><figcaption>Salmon jumping at Baileys Chute in Wells Gray Provincial Park<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<\/div>\n<div class=\"mv-ad-box\" data-slotid=\"content_4_btf\">\n<div class=\"mv-rail-frame-440\" data-slotid=\"content_4_btf\">\n<div class=\"mv-rail-slide-440 mv-inview-sticky\" data-slotid=\"content_4_btf\">\n<div class=\"mv-rail-sticky-440 mv-inview-sticky\" data-slotid=\"content_4_btf\">\n<div id=\"content_4_btf_wrapper\" class=\"adunitwrapper content_btf_wrapper mv-size-300x250 mv-dynamic-size\" data-wrapper=\"content_4_btf\" data-nosnippet=\"\">\n<div id=\"content_4_btf\" class=\"content_btf adunit\" data-google-query-id=\"CPLDr9PwyoIDFamYZgIdq14DhQ\">\n<div id=\"google_ads_iframe_\/1030006,22612110969\/offtracktravel\/content_15__container__\"><\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<h3><strong>Why is the salmon run so important?<\/strong><\/h3>\n<p>The return of salmon to BC\u2019s rivers is an important event not only for the salmon but also for other wildlife. Salmon are a vital source of food for bears, eagles, wolves, bald eagles and many other animals.<br \/>\nSalmon are also\u00a0part of the spiritual and cultural identity of many First Nations in BC. Not just a food source, salmon has provided wealth and trade opportunities for thousands of years.<\/p>\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-medium\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" id=\"mv-trellis-img-5\" class=\"wp-image-32934 lazyload\" src=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Chun-Lun-adams-river-1000x667.jpg.webp\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 760px) calc(100vw - 20px), 720px\" srcset=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Chun-Lun-adams-river-1000x667.jpg.webp 1000w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Chun-Lun-adams-river-300x200.jpg.webp 300w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Chun-Lun-adams-river-768x512.jpg.webp 768w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Chun-Lun-adams-river-960x640.jpg.webp 960w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Chun-Lun-adams-river-1080x720.jpg.webp 1080w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Chun-Lun-adams-river-150x100.jpg.webp 150w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Chun-Lun-adams-river.jpg.webp 1200w\" alt=\"Sockeye salmon in Adams River near Shuswap Lake. People on bridge in background, river is surrounded by forest\" width=\"1000\" height=\"667\" data-pin-media=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Chun-Lun-adams-river.jpg\" data-trellis-processed=\"1\" \/><figcaption>Adams River, photo credit: Destination BC \/ Chun Lun (please note that the 2023 wildfires have heavily impacted this area)<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<\/div>\n<h2>The best places to see the salmon run in British Columbia<\/h2>\n<p>The following locations are some of the most popular places to watch the salmon run in British Columbia. Each featured place is very accessible, with easy road access and marked trails.<br \/>\nDon\u2019t think, however, that these are the\u00a0<em>only\u00a0<\/em>places to go! Salmon spawn in rivers across British Columbia and there are many alternative locations. See the next section for more details.<\/p>\n<h3><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><strong>Goldstream Provincial Park, near Victoria<\/strong><\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><a href=\"https:\/\/bcparks.ca\/goldstream-park\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Goldstream Provincial Park<\/a>\u00a0is Vancouver Island\u2019s premier spot to watch the salmon run. The return of thousands of chum salmon is the main event, but coho, chinook and steelhead all spawn here as well.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">The riverside trails provide many excellent vantage points to watch the salmon swim up the waterway. I\u2019d recommend visiting the Nature House first to learn more about the wildlife in the park. Bald eagles are a common sight along the river, as they swoop down to eat salmon carcasses.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Due to the close proximity to Victoria, Goldstream is usually very busy on weekends during the peak of the salmon run season. Consider going early (before 10am) or late (4pm) to beat the crowds.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><em>Best time to go:<\/em> End of October<\/span><\/h3>\n<h3><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><strong>Puntledge River, Courtenay<\/strong><\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">There are many different places to spot the salmon run in Courtenay on Vancouver Island. Chinook, pink, coho, and chum all return to this area. We lived in Courtenay for a couple of years and loved seeing the salmon in fall.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">One of the most accessible salmon run locations is the\u00a0<strong>Puntledge River Hatchery<\/strong>, less than 10 minutes drive from downtown Courtenay. The facility features multiple river viewing points as well as a huge tank with glass windows.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Just downstream from the hatchery is\u00a0<strong>Puntledge Park<\/strong>. A loop trail leads through the riverside park, with plenty of opportunities to see the salmon in Puntledge River and neighbouring Morrison Creek. Black bears love to hang out near the salmon too, so be sure to keep alert!<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">At\u00a0<a href=\"https:\/\/www.comoxvalleyrd.ca\/parks-recreation\/comox-valley-parks-trails\/nymph-falls-nature-park\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Nymph Falls<\/a>, watch the salmon leap as they climb the man-made fish ladder on the Puntledge. The waterfall is 1km return from the parking lot, on a wheelchair-accessible trail.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><em>Best time to go:<\/em> Late September, early October<\/span><\/h3>\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-medium\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" id=\"mv-trellis-img-6\" class=\"wp-image-32703 lazyload\" src=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/Puntledge-river-autumn-1000x750.jpg.webp\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 760px) calc(100vw - 20px), 720px\" srcset=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/Puntledge-river-autumn-1000x750.jpg.webp 1000w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/Puntledge-river-autumn-267x200.jpg.webp 267w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/Puntledge-river-autumn-768x576.jpg.webp 768w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/Puntledge-river-autumn-728x546.jpg.webp 728w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/Puntledge-river-autumn-960x720.jpg.webp 960w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/Puntledge-river-autumn-1080x810.jpg.webp 1080w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/Puntledge-river-autumn-853x640.jpg.webp 853w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/Puntledge-river-autumn-150x113.jpg.webp 150w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/Puntledge-river-autumn.jpg.webp 1200w\" alt=\"Side view of Puntledge River in autumn with man-made dam, rocks and cascading water, with autumn colour trees in background\" width=\"1000\" height=\"750\" data-pin-media=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/07\/Puntledge-river-autumn.jpg\" data-trellis-processed=\"1\" \/><\/span><figcaption><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Puntledge River in autumn, near the hatchery<\/span><\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<\/div>\n<h3><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><strong>Stamp River Provincial Park, near Port Alberni<br \/>\n<\/strong>The Stamp River has to be one of the most impressive places to watch the salmon run in British Columbia.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Hundreds of salmon congregate in the pool below\u00a0<a href=\"https:\/\/bcparks.ca\/stamp-river-park\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Stamp River Falls\u00a0<\/a>before leaping up the fish ladder. Steep mossy canyon walls rise above the river, with autumn foliage above. A 2km trail follows the edge, offering several viewpoints along the way.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Black bears are a common sight in this area, as well as bald eagles.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">The salmon run season at Stamp River starts in late August, when the sockeye arrive. The coho and chinook start joining them in late September.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><em>Best time to go:\u00a0<\/em>Early to mid October<\/span><\/h3>\n<h3><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><strong>Capilano Hatchery, North Vancouver<br \/>\n<\/strong>Located in\u00a0<a href=\"https:\/\/metrovancouver.org\/services\/regional-parks\/park\/capilano-river-regional-park\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Capilano River Regional Park<\/a>, this hatchery is a popular place for viewing salmon all year round. The facility raises and releases more than one million salmon every year.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">The main attraction here is the fish ladder, where chinook and coho leap from step to step. The hatchery has an interpretive centre with underwater windows.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Make the most of your visit with a walk along the river, where you\u2019ll find more viewpoints and salmon sightings.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Don\u2019t have a car? Capilano Hatchery is accessible by bus!<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><em>Best time to go:<\/em>October<\/span><\/h3>\n<h3><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><strong>Adams River, between Kamloops and Salmon Arm<br \/>\n<\/strong>No list of the best spots to watch the salmon run in British Columbia would be complete without mention of the Adams River. This waterway is host to North America\u2019s largest Sockeye run. Chinook, Coho and pink salmon also spawn here.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Occupying both sides of the river,\u00a0<a href=\"https:\/\/bcparks.ca\/tsutswecw-park\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Ts\u00fatswecw (Roderick Haig-Brown) Provincial Park<\/a>\u00a0was the perfect place to watch the salmon run. Unfortunately, the 2023 wildfires in this area have heavily impacted the park. It is unknown when\/if it will be possible to safely watch the salmon here again.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">The Adams River Salmon Society celebrates the dominant run every four years with the\u00a0<a href=\"https:\/\/www.salmonsociety.com\/salute-to-the-sockeye\/event-details\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Salute to the Sockeye festival<\/a>. It will next take place from 30th September to 23rd October 2026.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><em>Best time to go:\u00a0<\/em>Early October<\/span><\/h3>\n<\/div>\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\" data-slot-rendered-content=\"true\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-medium\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" id=\"mv-trellis-img-7\" class=\"wp-image-32936 lazyload\" src=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Josh-Humbert-Adams-River-salmon-1000x667.jpg.webp\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 760px) calc(100vw - 20px), 720px\" srcset=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Josh-Humbert-Adams-River-salmon-1000x667.jpg.webp 1000w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Josh-Humbert-Adams-River-salmon-300x200.jpg.webp 300w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Josh-Humbert-Adams-River-salmon-768x512.jpg.webp 768w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Josh-Humbert-Adams-River-salmon-960x640.jpg.webp 960w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Josh-Humbert-Adams-River-salmon-1080x720.jpg.webp 1080w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Josh-Humbert-Adams-River-salmon-150x100.jpg.webp 150w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Josh-Humbert-Adams-River-salmon.jpg.webp 1200w\" alt=\"Water view looking up to bright red salmon above\" width=\"1000\" height=\"667\" data-pin-media=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Josh-Humbert-Adams-River-salmon.jpg\" data-trellis-processed=\"1\" \/><\/span><figcaption><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Salmon in the Adams River, photo credit: Destination BC \/ Josh Humbert<\/span><\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<\/div>\n<h2><strong><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Other great places to see spawning salmon in British Columbia<\/span><\/strong><\/h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">There are so many places to watch the salmon run in BC! When in doubt, head for a local salmon hatchery. These facilities often feature riverside trails, viewpoints and observation areas.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">The following list features even more great places to watch the salmon run in BC. While it is not a definitive list of every salmon run in the province (that would be SO long!), it provides a good overview.<\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><strong>Vancouver Island<\/strong><\/span><\/p>\n<ul data-slot-rendered-content=\"true\">\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Sproat Falls Fish Ladder, Port Alberni<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Woodstream Park, Nanaimo<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Little Qualicum River Hatchery, Qualicum Beach<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Big Qualicum Hatchery, Qualicum Beach<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Millard Creek, Courtenay<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Quinsam River Hatchery, Campbell River<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Marble River Provincial Park near Port Hardy<\/span><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<h3><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><strong>Lower Mainland and Coast<\/strong><\/span><\/h3>\n<ul>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Hoy Creek Hatchery, Coquitlam<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Little Campbell River Hatchery, Surrey<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Kanaka Creek Park Fish Fence, Maple Ridge<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">McClughan Park onYorkson Creek, Langley<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Cariboo Dam, Burnaby<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Weaver Creek spawning channel, Harrison Mills<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Chehalis River Hatchery, Agassiz<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Thacker Regional Park, Hope<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Mamquam River spawning channels, Squamish<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Tenderfoot Creek Hatchery, Squamish<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Alex Dobler Salmon Centre, Powell River<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">John Daly Park, Madeira Park<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Chapman Creek, Sechelt<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Louise Dover Trail Viewing Area (Haans Creek), Haida Gwaii<\/span><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<h3><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><strong>Interior BC<\/strong><\/span><\/h3>\n<ul data-slot-rendered-content=\"true\">\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Penticton Creek, Penticton<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Hardy Falls, Peachland<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Mission Creek, Kelowna<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Kingfisher Interpretive Centre, near Enderby<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">McDonald\u2019s Landing Regional Park, Nelson<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Kokanee Creek Provincial Park, Nelson<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Baileys Chute Trail, Wells Gray Provincial Park, Clearwater<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">George Hicks Regional Park, Swift Creek near Valemount<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Rearguard Falls Provincial Park (Fraser River) near Mount Robson<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Horsefly River Trail, Horsefly<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Cariboo Falls near Likely<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Cottonwood Island Nature Park, Prince George<\/span><\/li>\n<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Williams Creek near Terrace<\/span><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<div class=\"mv-ad-box\" data-slotid=\"content_10_btf\">\n<div class=\"mv-rail-frame-440\" data-slotid=\"content_10_btf\">\n<div class=\"mv-rail-slide-440 mv-inview-sticky\" data-slotid=\"content_10_btf\">\n<div class=\"mv-rail-sticky-440 mv-inview-sticky\" data-slotid=\"content_10_btf\">\n<div id=\"content_10_btf_wrapper\" class=\"adunitwrapper content_btf_wrapper mv-size-728x90 mv-dynamic-size\" data-wrapper=\"content_10_btf\" data-nosnippet=\"\"><\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<\/div>\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-medium\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" id=\"mv-trellis-img-8\" class=\"wp-image-32935 lazyload\" src=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Blake-Jorgenson-salmon-cariboo-falls-1000x668.jpg.webp\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 760px) calc(100vw - 20px), 720px\" srcset=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Blake-Jorgenson-salmon-cariboo-falls-1000x668.jpg.webp 1000w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Blake-Jorgenson-salmon-cariboo-falls-300x200.jpg.webp 300w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Blake-Jorgenson-salmon-cariboo-falls-768x513.jpg.webp 768w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Blake-Jorgenson-salmon-cariboo-falls-960x641.jpg.webp 960w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Blake-Jorgenson-salmon-cariboo-falls-1080x721.jpg.webp 1080w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Blake-Jorgenson-salmon-cariboo-falls-150x100.jpg.webp 150w, https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Blake-Jorgenson-salmon-cariboo-falls.jpg.webp 1200w\" alt=\"Salmon attempting to leap up raging waterfall in canyon\" width=\"1000\" height=\"668\" data-pin-media=\"https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/wp-content\/uploads\/2023\/09\/Destination-BC-Blake-Jorgenson-salmon-cariboo-falls.jpg\" data-trellis-processed=\"1\" \/><figcaption>Kokanee salmon at Cariboo Falls near Likely, photo credit: Destination BC \/ Blake Jorgenson<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n<\/div>\n<h2><strong>Important salmon run info<\/strong><\/h2>\n<p>When planning a trip to see the salmon run, please keep in the following in mind:<\/p>\n<ul data-slot-rendered-content=\"true\">\n<li>Be as quiet as possible. Noise can disturb the salmon. Approach the riverbank slowly and softly<\/li>\n<li>Consider leaving your dog at home. If you do bring your dog, keep them on a leash and stay back from the water<\/li>\n<li>Bring polarised sunglasses. These help with the glare of the water and will enable you to see the salmon better<\/li>\n<li>Consider binoculars, not for the salmon, but the wildlife attracted by them!<\/li>\n<li>If you can, go earlier rather than later. Closer to the end of the salmon run, it can get a little stinky. It\u2019s a sad (and smelly) fact that the salmon die during this process so fish carcasses are an inevitable part of the salmon run<\/li>\n<li>Following on from the above point, keep in mind that there are plenty of animals that enjoy feasting on the salmon. Stay alert, make noise, keep your distance and always give wildlife an escape route<\/li>\n<li>There are pretty strict restrictions regarding fishing on salmon spawning rivers.\u00a0<a href=\"https:\/\/www2.gov.bc.ca\/gov\/content\/sports-culture\/recreation\/fishing-hunting\/fishing\/recreational-freshwater-fishing-licence\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Buy the appropriate licence<\/a>\u00a0and double-check for closures and restrictions before planning a trip<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Where to See the Salmon Run in British Columbia: Complete Guide Excerpted from https:\/\/offtracktravel.ca\/Published September 2023 As the Pacific salmon swim from the ocean to the spawning grounds of their birth, British Columbia becomes the host of one of the &hellip; <a href=\"https:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/2023\/11\/17\/the-salmon-run-in-british-columbia\/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&rarr;<\/span><\/a><\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":0,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"jetpack_post_was_ever_published":false,"_jetpack_newsletter_access":"","_jetpack_dont_email_post_to_subs":false,"_jetpack_newsletter_tier_id":0,"_jetpack_memberships_contains_paywalled_content":false,"_jetpack_memberships_contains_paid_content":false,"footnotes":"","jetpack_publicize_message":"","jetpack_publicize_feature_enabled":true,"jetpack_social_post_already_shared":true,"jetpack_social_options":{"image_generator_settings":{"template":"highway","default_image_id":0,"enabled":false},"version":2}},"categories":[1],"tags":[],"class_list":["post-19161","post","type-post","status-publish","format-standard","hentry","category-uncategorized"],"aioseo_notices":[],"jetpack_publicize_connections":[],"jetpack_featured_media_url":"